GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 947
Short Title: Every Child Reads. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Cotham, Biggs, and Brockman (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Education - K-12, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PROVIDE FOR DYSLEXIA SCREENING AND INTERVENTIONS IN
3 SCHOOLS, TO REQUIRE DYSLEXIA TRAINING FOR TEACHERS, TO REQUIRE
4 LITERACY INSTRUCTION IN MIDDLE SCHOOLS BE ALIGNED WITH THE
5 SCIENCE OF READING, AND TO TRANSFER THE NC PRE-K PROGRAM TO THE
6 DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC INSTRUCTION.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8
9 PART I. DYSLEXIA SCREENINGS AND INTERVENTIONS
10 SECTION 1.(a) Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
11 Article to read:
12 "Article 9D.
13 "Students with Dyslexia.
14 "§ 115C-150.20. Purpose.
15 It is the intent of the General Assembly that all students with dyslexia receive the necessary
16 and appropriate screenings, assessments, and special education services providing interventions
17 for learning difficulties with language, reading, and writing. To provide a common set of
18 professional standards and guidelines for the identification of and intervention for students with
19 dyslexia, the State Board of Education and local boards of education shall implement a screening
20 process, comprehensive assessment, and intervention strategies for these students in accordance
21 with the provisions of this Article and Article 9 of this Chapter.
22 "§ 115C-150.21. Definitions.
23 The following definitions apply in this Article:
24 (1) Disability. – As defined in G.S. 115C-106.3(2).
25 (2) Dyslexia. – A disorder in one or more of the basic psychological processes
26 involved in the understanding or in using language, spoken or written,
27 characterized by difficulty with accurate or fluent word recognition, or both,
28 and by difficulty with spelling and decoding.
29 (3) Individualized education program or IEP. – As defined in
30 G.S. 115C-106.3(6).
31 (4) Science of Reading. – As defined in G.S. 115C-83.3(7a).
32 (5) Special education. – As defined in G.S. 115C-106.3(20).
33 "§ 115C-150.22. Screening, assessment, and intervention.
34 (a) The State Board of Education shall provide informational materials and screening
35 instruments developed in accordance with G.S. 115C-12(50) to local boards of education to
*H947-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 identify students who exhibit potential indicators of dyslexia. Each local board of education shall
2 provide informational materials related to dyslexia to parents of students who exhibit potential
3 indicators of dyslexia on an annual basis.
4 (b) Local school administrative units shall screen every student in grades kindergarten
5 through three, grade six, and grade nine for dyslexia using the screening instrument adopted by
6 the State Board.
7 (c) If a screening instrument indicates that a student exhibits potential indicators of
8 dyslexia, the local school administrative unit shall administer a comprehensive assessment
9 adopted by the State Board to determine whether the student has dyslexia. A student identified
10 as having dyslexia shall be provided appropriate intervention strategies grounded in the Science
11 of Reading through the student's individualized education program in accordance with the rules
12 adopted by the State Board.
13 "§ 115C-150.23. Training for school personnel.
14 (a) All grades kindergarten through three, grade six, and grade nine teachers shall be
15 trained to administer the screening instruments provided by the State Board pursuant to
16 G.S. 115C-150.22.
17 (b) Ongoing professional development opportunities shall be made available to teachers
18 and other school personnel on the identification of and intervention strategies for students with
19 dyslexia."
20 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 115C-12 is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
21 "(50) Informational Materials and Screening for Dyslexia. – The State Board of
22 Education shall develop informational materials to be shared with parents
23 regarding dyslexia. The State Board of Education shall adopt age-appropriate
24 screening instruments, a comprehensive assessment for students who exhibit
25 potential indicators for dyslexia, and appropriate intervention strategies
26 grounded in the Science of Reading for use by local boards of education."
27 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 115C-83.10(b) reads as rewritten:
28 "(b) Each local board of education shall report annually in writing to the State Board of
29 Education by September 1 of each year the following information on the prior school year:
30 (1) A description of all literacy interventions provided to students who have been
31 retained under G.S. 115C-83.7(a).
32 (1a) A description of the literacy interventions provided to (i) students who exhibit
33 potential indicators of dyslexia and (ii) students with dyslexia.
34 (2) The number of first and second grade students attending a reading camp
35 offered by the local board.
36 (3) The license area or areas, years of licensed teaching experience, grade level
37 assignment, and any other specific subject-area assignments of each teacher
38 providing instruction at a reading camp.
39 (4) The number and percentage of teachers providing instruction at a reading
40 camp who were paid a reading performance bonus during the school year
41 immediately preceding the reading camp and the grade level on which the
42 bonus was based.
43 (5) The number of kindergarten through third grade students with an Individual
44 Reading Plan."
45 SECTION 1.(d) G.S. 115C-83.6A(a) reads as rewritten:
46 "(a) Each local school administrative unit shall submit to the Department of Public
47 Instruction a plan for the literacy interventions it will offer, including reading camps, in the
48 following school year no later than October 1. The plan shall include information about the
49 specific literacy interventions and literacy curricula that will be used with (i) students who exhibit
50 potential indicators of dyslexia and (ii) students with dyslexia. The plan shall include information
51 about the local school administrative unit's efforts to staff reading camps with the most qualified
Page 2 House Bill 947-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 teachers possible, including the unit's efforts to attract teachers associated with high growth in
2 reading based on EVAAS data and teachers who have earned a reading bonus. The plan shall
3 incorporate any feedback received from the Department on the previous year's plan. As part of
4 their plans, local school administrative units are encouraged to partner with other local school
5 administrative units and with community organizations to enhance literacy interventions."
6 SECTION 1.(e) G.S. 115C-83.6B(a) reads as rewritten:
7 "(a) An Individual Reading Plan (IRP) shall be developed for any student in kindergarten
8 through third grade demonstrating difficulty with reading development based on the results of
9 either (i) the first diagnostic or formative assessment of the school year or (ii) the first diagnostic
10 or formative assessment of the second semester of the school year. The IRP shall be continually
11 adjusted based on multiple data sources as prescribed by the Department of Public Instruction,
12 including the results of any dyslexia screening performed in accordance with G.S. 115C-150.22,
13 indicating that the student is not progressing toward grade-level standards in one or more major
14 reading areas. Based on the most recently collected data, the IRP shall include the following
15 information, specific to the identified student:
16 (1) The specific reading skill deficiencies identified by assessment data.
17 (2) Goals and benchmarks for growth.
18 (3) The means by which progress will be monitored and evaluated.
19 (4) The specific additional literacy interventions the student will receive.
20 (5) The Science of Reading-based instructional programming the teacher will
21 implement.
22 (6) Any additional services the teacher deems appropriate to accelerate the
23 student's reading skill and development."
24 SECTION 1.(f) Each local board of education shall report to the State Board of
25 Education on the following information by September 15, 2026:
26 (1) A description of the literacy interventions provided to students who exhibit
27 potential indicators of dyslexia, which includes difficulty with accurate or
28 fluent word recognition, or both, and difficulty with spelling and decoding.
29 (2) A description of the literacy interventions provided to students with dyslexia.
30 (3) A list and description of any literacy curricula being used with students with
31 dyslexia.
32 (4) A list and description of the professional development offered to teachers in
33 the local school administrative unit that includes instruction on identifying and
34 providing interventions for students with dyslexia. This shall include the
35 number of teachers who have participated in the professional development.
36 The State Board of Education shall report the information provided by the local
37 boards of education, with an executive summary and disaggregated by local school
38 administrative units, to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee by November 15,
39 2026.
40 SECTION 1.(g) This section is effective when it becomes law. Subsections (a), (b),
41 and (e) of this section apply beginning with the 2026-2027 school year. Subsection (c) of this
42 section applies beginning with the report submitted by September 1, 2027. Subsection (d) of this
43 section applies beginning with literacy intervention plans submitted by October 1, 2026.
44
45 PART II. EARLY LITERACY PROGRAM
46 SECTION 2. G.S. 115C-83.4B(b) reads as rewritten:
47 "(b) As part of the Early Literacy Program, the Department of Public Instruction shall
48 focus on at least the following components:
49 (1) Provide a training program to educators and administrators working with
50 children in the NC Pre-K program to ensure developmentally appropriate
51 instruction grounded in the Science of Reading and outcomes promoting
House Bill 947-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 reading achievement in students. The Department of Public Instruction shall
2 utilize a third-party independent teacher training program to deliver
3 professional development that demonstrates evidence-based success with
4 educators and administrators in establishing deep knowledge of literacy
5 instruction.
6 (2) Provide integration of age-appropriate resources, including digital and
7 technological resources, in the NC Pre-K program for children to meet reading
8 achievement goals.
9 (3) Ensure administration of a formative assessment to children at the conclusion
10 of their participation in the NC Pre-K program to determine their kindergarten
11 readiness and the alignment of their literacy instruction with the Science of
12 Reading. The Department shall also ensure that the results of each child's
13 formative assessment are shared with the child's kindergarten teacher at the
14 beginning of the next school year.
15 (4) Ensure administration of a dyslexia screening instrument to every student
16 participating in the NC Pre-K program. The Department shall ensure that the
17 results of each child's screening are shared with the child's kindergarten
18 teacher at the beginning of the next school year.
19 (5) Provide training to educators and administrators working with children in the
20 NC Pre-K program to ensure appropriate instruction and intervention
21 strategies are used with students who exhibit potential indicators of dyslexia."
22
23 PART III. EDUCATOR PREPARATION AND CONTINUING LICENSURE
24 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 115C-269.20(a)(3) reads as rewritten:
25 "(3) EPPs providing training for elementary and special education general
26 curriculum teachers shall ensure that students receive instruction in early
27 literacy intervention strategies and practices that are aligned with the Science
28 of Reading and State and national reading standards and shall include the
29 following:
30 a. Instruction in the teaching of reading, including a substantive
31 understanding of reading as a process involving oral language,
32 phonological and phonemic awareness, phonics, fluency, vocabulary,
33 and comprehension. Instruction shall include appropriate application
34 of literacy interventions to ensure reading proficiency for all students.
35 b. Instruction in evidence-based assessment and diagnosis of specific
36 areas of difficulty with reading development and of reading
37 deficiencies.
38 c. Instruction in appropriate application of literacy interventions to
39 ensure reading proficiency for all students.
40 d. Instruction in the identification of and intervention strategies for
41 students with dyslexia."
42 SECTION 3.(b) G.S. 115C-269.20(a)(4) reads as rewritten:
43 "(4) EPPs providing training for middle and high school teachers shall include the
44 following:
45 a. Adequate coursework in the relevant content area. For clinical
46 residency programs, students may instead demonstrate mastery of the
47 relevant content area through the passage of the relevant content area
48 examination approved by the State Board.
49 b. Adequate coursework in the teaching of the relevant content area.
50 c. For EPPs providing training for science teachers, adequate preparation
51 in issues related to science laboratory safety.
Page 4 House Bill 947-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 d. Instruction in the identification of and intervention strategies for
2 students with dyslexia."
3 SECTION 3.(c) G.S. 115C-270.30(b)(2) reads as rewritten:
4 "(2) For elementary school teachers, teachers and middle school teachers teaching
5 under a Middle Grades license, at least three continuing education credits
6 related to literacy. Literacy renewal credits shall include evidence-based
7 assessment, diagnosis, and intervention strategies for students not
8 demonstrating reading proficiency, grounded in the Science of Reading, as
9 defined in G.S. 115C-83.3. At least one credit shall include instruction in the
10 identification of and intervention strategies for students with dyslexia."
11
12 PART IV. MIDDLE SCHOOL LITERACY INSTRUCTION
13 SECTION 4. Article 8 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by adding
14 a new section to read:
15 "§ 115C-81.37. Literacy instruction in middle schools.
16 To the extent literacy instruction is provided, all literacy instruction in middle schools shall
17 be aligned with the Science of Reading, as defined in G.S. 115C-83.3."
18
19 PART V. RELOCATE NC PRE-K FROM DHHS TO DPI
20 SECTION 5.(a) The NC Prekindergarten (NC Pre-K) program is transferred from
21 the Department of Health and Human Services to the Department of Public Instruction effective
22 July 1, 2025. This transfer shall have all of the elements of a Type I transfer, as defined in
23 G.S. 143A-6(a). All duties and requirements associated with NC Pre-K are now the duty and
24 responsibility of the Department of Public Instruction to fulfill.
25 SECTION 5.(b) G.S. 143B-168.10A reads as rewritten:
26 "§ 143B-168.10A. NC Pre-K Reports.
27 The Division of Child Development and Early Education Department of Public Instruction
28 shall submit an annual report no later than March 15 of each year to the Joint Legislative
29 Commission on Governmental Operations, the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health
30 and Human Services, the Senate Appropriations Committee on Health and Human Services, the
31 House of Representatives Appropriations Subcommittee on Health and Human Services, the
32 Office of State Budget and Management, the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee,
33 and the Fiscal Research Division. The report shall include the following:
34 (1) The number of children participating in the NC Pre-K program.
35 (2) The number of children participating in the NC Pre-K program who have
36 never been served in other early education programs, such as child care, public
37 or private preschool, Head Start, Early Head Start, or early intervention
38 programs.
39 (3) The expected NC Pre-K expenditures for the programs and the source of the
40 local contributions.
41 (4) The results of an annual evaluation of the NC Pre-K program."
42 SECTION 5.(c) G.S. 143B-168.10F(a) reads as rewritten:
43 "(a) The Division of Childhood Development and Early Education of the Department of
44 Health and Human Services Department of Public Instruction shall post the following
45 information on its website:
46 (1) The educational opportunities for kindergarten offered by local school
47 administrative units.
48 (2) The educational opportunities for kindergarten offered by charter schools.
49 (3) Scholarships for enrollment in nonpublic schools provided pursuant to Part
50 2A of Article 39 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes, or any successor
51 program.
House Bill 947-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 This information shall be indexed or searchable by county, and the
2 Division Department shall update the information on June 1 each year."
3 SECTION 5.(d) NC Pre-K Program. – The Department of Public Instruction shall
4 comply with the following provisions:
5 (1) Eligibility. – The Department of Public Instruction shall continue
6 implementing the NC Prekindergarten (NC Pre-K) program. The NC Pre-K
7 program shall serve children who are 4 years of age on or before August 31
8 of the program year. In determining eligibility, the Department shall establish
9 income eligibility requirements for the program not to exceed seventy-five
10 percent (75%) of the State median income. Up to twenty percent (20%) of
11 children enrolled may have family incomes in excess of seventy-five percent
12 (75%) of median income if those children have other designated risk factors.
13 Furthermore, any age-eligible child who is a child of either of the following
14 shall be eligible for the program: (i) an active duty member of the Armed
15 Forces of the United States, including the North Carolina National Guard,
16 State military forces, or a reserve component of the Armed Forces who was
17 ordered to active duty by the proper authority within the last 18 months or is
18 expected to be ordered within the next 18 months, or (ii) a member of the
19 Armed Forces of the United States, including the North Carolina National
20 Guard, State military forces, or a reserve component of the Armed Forces who
21 was injured or killed while serving on active duty. Eligibility determinations
22 for NC Pre-K participants may continue through local education agencies and
23 local North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., partnerships. Other than
24 developmental disabilities or other chronic health issues, the Department shall
25 not consider the health of a child as a factor in determining eligibility for
26 participation in the NC Pre-K program.
27 (2) Staff-to-child ratio and class size. – The classroom shall not exceed a
28 maximum staff-to-child ratio of one to 10 with a maximum class size of 20
29 children, with at least one teacher and one teacher assistant per classroom. A
30 classroom of 10 children or less shall have at least one teacher. The Child Care
31 Commission shall adopt any rules, and the Department of Public Instruction
32 shall revise any rules or policies necessary to implement the provisions of this
33 subdivision.
34 (3) Multiyear contracts. – The Department of Public Instruction shall require the
35 NC Pre-K contractor to issue multiyear contracts for licensed private child
36 care centers providing NC Pre-K classrooms.
37 (4) Building standards. – Notwithstanding G.S. 110-91(4), private child care
38 facilities and public schools operating NC Pre-K classrooms shall meet the
39 building standards for preschool students as provided in G.S. 115C-521.1.
40 (5) Programmatic standards. – Except as provided in subdivision (3) of this
41 subsection, entities operating NC Pre-K classrooms shall adhere to all of the
42 policies prescribed by the Department of Public Instruction regarding
43 programmatic standards and classroom requirements.
44 (6) NC Pre-K committees. – Local NC Pre-K committees shall use the standard
45 decision-making process developed by the Department of Public Instruction
46 in awarding NC Pre-K classroom slots and student selection.
47 (7) Reporting. – The Department of Public Instruction shall submit an annual
48 report no later than March 15 of each year to the Joint Legislative Education
49 Oversight Committee, the Office of State Budget and Management, and the
50 Fiscal Research Division. The report shall include the following:
Page 6 House Bill 947-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. The number of children participating in the NC Pre-K program by
2 county.
3 b. The number of children participating in the NC Pre-K program who
4 have never been served in other early education programs such as child
5 care, public or private preschool, Head Start, Early Head Start, or early
6 intervention programs.
7 c. The expected NC Pre-K expenditures for the programs and the source
8 of the local contributions.
9 d. The results of an annual evaluation of the NC Pre-K program.
10 (8) Audits. – The administration of the NC Pre-K program by local partnerships
11 shall be subject to the financial and compliance audits authorized under
12 G.S. 143B-168.14(b).
13
14 PART VI. EFFECTIVE DATE
15 SECTION 6. This act is effective when it becomes law and applies beginning with
16 the 2025-2026 school year.
